-- Tata Steel Surges on Optimism Europe’s Debt Crisis Is Easing
-- B y   A b h i s h e k   S h a n k e r
-- 2012-01-13T08:51:58Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-13/tata-steel-surges-on-optimism-europe-s-debt-crisis-is-easing.html
Tata Steel Ltd. (TATA)  gained the most in
32 months in Mumbai on optimism demand is set to rise in  India 
in the current quarter and the debt crisis is easing in  Europe ,
which accounts for two-thirds of the company’s production.  The shares of India’s biggest steelmaker rose as much as
9.2 percent, the most since May 2009, to 424.75 rupees and
traded at 421.75 rupees as of 1:28 p.m. local time.  Borrowing costs fell for Spain and Italy at debt sales
yesterday, while European Central Bank President  Mario Draghi 
said he saw “tentative signs” of stabilization in the euro
region. Steel sales are rising in India as contractors of public
works accelerate projects to meet government deadlines for the
year ending March 31.  “There are clear signs demand is reviving,” said Abhisar
Jain, an analyst at Centrum Broking Pvt. in Mumbai.
“Consumption may rise this quarter, especially in India.”  Steel consumption in India is higher than in other markets
and Tata Steel expects demand to grow as much as 8 percent in
the financial year ending March 31, 2013, Vice Chairman B. Muthuraman said yesterday.  Steel Authority of India Ltd. , the second-largest producer,
gained as much as 4.6 percent to 95.55 rupees and traded at
93.75 rupees.  JSW Steel Ltd. (JSTL)  rose as much as 4.9 percent to
662.80 rupees and traded at 658.75 rupees.  India’s government plans to double its spending on public
works and utility projects to $1 trillion in the five years
ending March 2017, aiming to achieve economic growth of 9
percent. The economy will expand about 7 percent in the year
ending March 31, Prime Minister  Manmohan Singh  said on Jan. 8,
less than his December prediction of 7.5 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
